  "prompt": "Are there legal obligations for financial institutions regarding money laundering?",
  "response": "Financial institutions have significant legal obligations to prevent money laundering, including:\n\n1. Know Your Customer (KYC) requirements\n- Verify customer identities\n- Conduct background checks\n- Monitor suspicious transactions\n\n2. Reporting requirements\n- File Suspicious Activity Reports (SARs)\n- Report large cash transactions\n- Notify authorities of potential money laundering activities\n\n3. Anti-Money Laundering (AML) compliance programs\n- Develop internal policies and procedures\n- Implement transaction monitoring systems\n- Conduct regular employee training\n\n4. Legal regulations\n- Comply with Bank Secrecy Act\n- Follow Financial Action Task Force (FATF) guidelines\n- Adhere to international anti-money laundering standards\n\n5. Record keeping\n- Maintain detailed transaction records\n- Retain documentation for specified periods\n- Ensure records are accessible for potential investigations\n\n6. Risk assessment\n- Evaluate customer and transaction risks\n- Implement enhanced due diligence for high-risk accounts\n- Continuously update risk management strategies\n\nFailure to comply can result in significant financial penalties, legal consequences, and potential loss of operating licenses.\n\nThese obligations aim to prevent criminal activities like terrorism financing and fraud.",
